n the end times and the final judgment. Within it, there is mention of a figure known as the �Beast of the Earth� or the �Second Beast�.\rThis second beast is described as emerging from the earth and having two horns like those of a lamb but speaking like a dragon. It exercises authority and performs deceptive signs and wonders, leading people to worship the first beast, which is identified as the Antichrist.\rThe Beast of the Earth is often interpreted as a symbol of the false prophet, a religious lead.er or deceptive influence that supports and promotes the worship of the first beast. It is seen as an evil force that seduces and deceives people, leading them away from the truth and the worship of God.\rThis apocalyptic figure has been the subject of interpretations and theological debates throughout history. Its inclusion in the apocalyptic narrative serves to convey religious teach.ings about the power of evil, the importance of faith, and divine judgment.\rIt is important to note that these interpretations are based on specific religious beliefs and traditions and may vary among different branches of Christianity.\r\r\rAqueronte\rO Rio e o Monstro Infernal\rO Aqueronte � uma figura central na mitologia e na literatura, assumindo diferentes formas ao longo da hist�ria. Na mitologia grega, � conhecido como o �rio do infort�nio�, um dos afluentes do Estige, que conduz as almas ao submundo. O barqueiro Caronte transporta os rec�m-mortos atra.v�s das suas �guas at� as portas do Hades, onde s�o recebidos por C�rbero. Esse rio, localizado na regi�o do Epiro, no noroeste da Gr�cia, tamb�m foi mencionado por Plat�o, que o descreveu como o segundo maior rio do mundo subterr�neo, fluindo na direc��o oposta ao Oceano.\rA presen�a do Aqueronte transcende a mitologia cl�ssica e manifesta-se em diversas obras liter�rias. Virg�lio menciona-o na Eneida, Dante Alighieri apresenta-o em �A Divina Com�dia� como a fronteira do Inferno, e escritores modernos, como Robert E. Howard, in