nd symbolic style inspired by Kabuki theatre. Their appearance is iconic: white makeup, elaborate kimono, and traditional hairstyles with specific ornaments for each stage of their career. The makeup of maiko is more striking, while more experienced geishas adopt a subtler look.\rAlthough the number of geishas has declined, they still exist in the hanamachi (geisha dis.tricts), especially in Kyoto and Tokyo. Their work remains a symbol of Japanese culture, repre.senting elegance, tradition, and refined artistry.\r\r\rHades\rHades, na mitologia grega, � o deus do submundo e dos mortos, filho de Cronos e Reia, e irm�o de Zeus e Pos�don. Governante implac�vel do mundo inferior, recebeu o reino subterr�.neo ap�s a vit�ria contra os Tit�s. � conhecido por seu rapto de Pers�fone, filha de Dem�ter, com quem reina sem ter descend�ncia. A uni�o simboliza a liga��o entre morte e renascimen.to, associando Hades � fertilidade e � riqueza do subsolo. Embora temido pelos mortais, Hades desempenha um papel essencial na ordem c�smica, sendo um deus severo, por�m justo, que raramente interage com o mundo dos vivos.\rHades\rHades, in Greek mythology, is the god of the underworld and the dead, son of Cronus and Rhea, and brother of Zeus and Poseidon. As the relentless ruler of the underworld, he was granted the subterranean realm after the victory against the Titans. He is known for his abduc.tion of Persephone, daughter of Demeter, with whom he reigns without having offspring. Their union symbolizes the connection between death and rebirth, associating Hades with fertility and the wealth of the underground. Though feared by mortals, Hades plays an essential role in the cosmic order, being a stern but just god who rarely interacts with the world of the living.\r\r\rHag, ou Crone\rA Hag, ou Crone, � uma figura presente em v�rias tradi��es mitol�gicas e folcl�ricas eu.ropeias (que poderia ser traduzida como bruxa). Ela � geralmente retratada como uma velha senhora de apar�ncia enrugada 