�licas no Dia de Guy Fawkes, a 5 de Novembro.\rNos s�culos XIX e XX, especialmente nos Estados Unidos, o Halloween transformou-se numa celebra��o popular, tornando-se um evento comercial, com fantasias, festas, filmes de terror e decora��es tem�ticas. Desde a d�cada de 1970, a festividade espalhou-se pelo mundo, incluin.do o Brasil, onde come�ou a ganhar popularidade nos anos 1990, impulsionada por escolas de idiomas e pela globaliza��o.\rApesar do seu car�cter festivo, o Halloween tem gerado controv�rsias, principalmente entre grupos religiosos, que o associam ao satanismo, embora n�o haja evid�ncias hist�ricas dessa liga��o. Al�m disso, em alguns pa�ses, h� resist�ncia � sua celebra��o devido � influ�ncia cul.tural norte-americana.\rActualmente, o Halloween continua a evoluir, sendo celebrado de diferentes formas em todo o mundo, mantendo elementos tradicionais como fantasias, doces, festas e hist�rias de terror.\rHalloween\rHalloween, celebrated on October 31st, has roots in both pagan festivals and Christian tra.ditions. It is believed to originate from the Celtic festival of Samhain, held in Ireland, Scotland, and the Isle of Man, marking the end of summer and the beginning of winter. The Celts believed that on this night, the veil between the living and the dead was thinner, allowing spirits to roam the earth. To appease them and ward off evil entities, they lit bonfires, left offerings, and wore masks to disguise themselves.\rWith the arrival of Christianity, the Catholic Church incorporated this tradition into its calen.dar, turning Samhain into All Hallows� Eve, which later became �Halloween�. In the 8th century, Pope Gregory III established All Saints� Day on November 1st, and in the 9th century, Pope Greg.ory IV made the date universal.\rThe custom of carving pumpkins (Jack-o�-lanterns) comes from an Irish legend about Stingy Jack, a man doomed to wander for eternity with only a hollowed-out turnip lit from within to guide him. When Irish immigrants arriv