essoas at� aos dias de hoje.\rHercules\rHercules, also known as Heracles in Greek mythology, is one of the most famous and revered heroes of classical mythology.\re was the son of Zeus, the king of the gods, and Alcmene, a mortal woman.\rThe story of Hercules is filled with adventures and heroic deeds. From birth, he faced many challenges and trials. His first notable feat was strangling two serpents sent to kill him when he was just a baby, demonstrating his strength and courage from a very young age.\rLater, as an adult, Hercules was condemned to perform twelve labors to atone for killing his wife and children in a fit of madness induced by Hera, Zeus�s jealous wife. The twelve labors included dangerous and nearly impossible tasks, such as defeating the Nemean Lion, slaying the Lernaean Hydra, and capturing Cerberus, the three-headed dog of the underworld.\rBeyond the twelve labors, Hercules also took part in many other adventures and challeng.es, facing monsters, gods, and other mythological beings. His unparalleled strength and brav.ery were his most notable traits, making him a legendary hero. However, despite his physical strength, Hercules was also known for his intelligence and wisdom. He was a complex hero, enduring hardships and trials while seeking redemption and immortality.\rThe story of Hercules has been widely depicted in art, literature, and cinema over the centu.ries. He is considered an emblem of heroism and perseverance, a symbol of human strength and the ability to overcome challenges. His story continues to inspire many people to this day.\r\rHidra de Lerna\rA Hidra de Lerna, criatura lend�ria da mitologia grega, era filha de Tif�o e Equidna. Repre.sentada como uma serpente monstruosa com um corpo de drag�o, possu�a v�rias cabe�as regenerativas � ao serem cortadas, duas novas nasciam. Segundo Diodoro, tinha cem cabe�as; a Biblioteca de Apolodoro descreve nove, sendo uma delas, imortal. A Hidra vivia nos p�ntanos de Lerna, na Arg�lida, espalhando