que a sua hist�ria sofreu modifica��es devido a erros de transcri��o ou mudan�as na tradi��o oral.\rKuy.th. \rKuy.th. is the cosmic ox of medieval Islamic cosmography. According to the accounts, he carries on his back the angel who supports the Earth, along with the stone platform on which the angel stands. The ox is positioned above the gigantic fish or whale known as Bahamut.\rIn the oldest sources, the ox is described as having 40,000 horns and legs, or, in other ver.sions, 40,000 eyes, ears, mouths, and tongues. These numbers may vary in later versions of the tradition. It is said that its breath controls the ocean tides.\rThe name Kuy.th. appears in the cosmography of al-Qazwini (d. 1283) and also in Shiite texts, where it is referred to by the variant name Lah.t. (according to Bih.r al-anw.r). Other versions include K.y.b.n and Kib.th.n, which appear in printed editions of Qazwini�s cosmog.raphy and have been interpreted as corruptions of Leviathan. Additional alternative names include Rakabo�n� and Al-Rayann.\rLater translations of the concept led to different forms of the name, such as Kuyoot�, Kuy.ooth�n, Kuyata (in Spanish), Kujata (in the first English translation, 1969), and Quyata (in the re.vised English translation). These variations appear in different editions of The Book of Imaginary Beings by Jorge Luis Borges.\rIt is believed that the figure of Kuy.th. evolved within the Arab tradition, possibly emerg.ing from the fusion of two biblical creatures: Behemoth and Leviathan. Islamic cosmography describes a creation process in which God forms the angel, the stone, and the ox in a specific order to ensure the stability of the Earth.\r\r\rBeyond its structural role in the cosmos, the cosmic ox is associated with natural and cosmic events, such as the regulation of sea levels and predictions about the Day of Judgment. Ancient Islamic texts describe how Bahamut and Kuy.th. support the Earth and the waters, reinforcing the belief that both play fundamental roles in the order of the universe.\rIslamic cosmography preserves the image of Kuy.th. as one of the great mythical beings of the universe. However, the diversity of names and variations over the centuries suggests that its story underwent modifications due to transcription errors or changes in oral tradition.\rO lado sombrio da religi�o e da b�blia \rA B�blia, para muitos, � um farol de esperan�a, uma colec��o de palavras que guia o esp�rito para a luz. Mas como todo o texto poderoso, nas m�os erradas, torna-se uma arma. No vasto campo de interpreta��es que ela permite, h� quem procure o amor, mas tamb�m quem encon.tre o �dio. H� quem a use para curar, mas tamb�m quem a transforme num instrumento de dor. Assim, o lado sombrio da religi�o surge, alimentado por cora��es que procuram dom�nio, n�o reden��o.\rA hist�ria revela momentos em que as palavras sagradas foram distorcidas para justificar atrocidades. Vers�culos arrancados do contexto tornaram-se gritos de guerra, escudos para a intoler�ncia e chamas que alimentaram fogueiras, reais e metaf�ricas. Em nome de Deus, ergueram-se cruzadas, ca�aram-se �bruxas�, exterminaram-se culturas inteiras. O mesmo livro que prega a compaix�o foi usado para impor sil�ncios, escravizar, submeter e destruir.\rAs seitas mais obscuras fazem desta pr�tica a sua bandeira. Envolvem os vulner�veis em promessas de salva��o, enquanto os conduzem a um inferno terreno. Citam palavras que su.postamente ecoam de c�us long�nquos, mas escondem nelas as suas pr�prias ambi��es. �Deus quer isso�, dizem, quando � apenas o desejo humano por controle que dita as suas ac��es.\rO horroroso lado da religi�o n�o est� na B�blia em si, mas no que os homens fazem com ela. N�o � o livro que � cruel, mas o uso perverso que dele se faz. Essa escurid�o surge sempre que a interpreta��o se fecha, sempre que a d�vida � proibida e a f� se torna um instrumento de medo. � um lembrete de que at� mesmo o que � considerado sagrado pode ser corrompido.\rNo entanto, esse lado sombrio n�o define a totalidade da B�blia ou da religi�o. Ele � uma sombra que s� existe porque a luz tamb�m est� presente. Cabe aos que procuram o verdadeiro sentido de f� e amor resgatar as palavras dos abismos onde foram jogadas, devolvendo-lhes o prop�sito de unir, e n�o de dividir; de curar, e n�o de ferir.\rAssim, o lado sombrio �, paradoxalmente, uma advert�ncia e um chamado: para que as pa.lavras de poder sejam manejadas com cuidado, com compaix�o e com a consci�ncia de que a interpreta��o nunca deve esmagar a dignidade humana.\rThe Dark Side of Religion and the Bible\rThe Bible, for many, is a beacon of hope, a collection of words that guides the spirit toward light. But like any powerful text, in the wrong hands, it becomes a weapon. In the vast field of interpretations it allows, some seek love, but others find hate. Some use it to heal, but others turn it into an instrument of pain. Thus, the dark side of religion emerges, fueled by hearts seeking domination, not redemption.\rHistory reveals moments when sacred words were twisted to justify atrocities. Verses torn from context became battle cries, shields for intolerance, and flames that fed fires�both literal and metaphorical. In the name of God, crusades were launched, �witches� were hunted, and en.tire cultures were annihilated. The same book that preaches compassion was used to enforce silence, enslave, subjugate, and destroy.\rThe most obscure sects make this practice their banner. They ensnare the vulnerable with promises of salvation while leading them into an earthly hell. They quote words that supposed.ly echo from distant heavens but hide within them their own ambitions. �God wills it�, they say, when it is merely human desire for control that dictates their actions.\rThe horrifying side of religion does not lie in the Bible itself but in what people do with it. It is not the book that is cruel, but the perverse use made of it. This darkness arises whenever interpretation becomes rigid, 