nd in the Antarctic seas. Her arms transform into wings, and her body is covered with silky down. In the romantic story �The Life and Adventures of Peter Wilkins� (1751) by Robert Paltock, Peter Wilkins shipwrecks and discovers Youwarkee, with whom he marries and has children.\rYouwarkee is described as a sweet creature, full of tenderness and liveliness. She possesses a natural sense of style and is a blessed companion. Her happiness is tied to Peter�s, and she does everything to satisfy his desires. She represents the essence of home and the grace of Peter�s imagination.\rIn the preface of the work, it is highlighted that Youwarkee is a charming and unparalleled character in literature. Unlike other winged women described in stories, she is not light or airy, but rather a sympathetic, loving, and endearing female figure. The author acknowledges the ingenious quality of creating a woman with elastic wings but also notes that, if it were more naturalistic, the creature could have been quite different, with wilder and less human charac.teristics.\rPeter�s encounter with Youwarkee is described as enchanting, where he awakens from his dreams to find the lovely winged woman at his door.\r\r\rZarat� / Aspidochelone\rZarat� e Aspidochelone s�o figuras centrais em lendas marinhas que percorrem v�rias cul.turas e �pocas, sempre associadas � ideia de criaturas gigantescas que se disfar�am de ilhas. Essas hist�rias reflectem o fasc�nio das culturas antigas pelo mist�rio do mar e pelo perigo que ele esconde. Ambas as criaturas partilham da capacidade de atrair navegantes com apar�ncia inofensiva de ilha, apenas para revelar a sua verdadeira natureza e levar � morte os que che.gam.\rA lenda do Zarat� remonta a fontes �rabes e europeias medievais. Nas obras do zo�logo mu�ulmano Al-Jahiz, do s�culo IX, os marinheiros contam sobre �ilhas� que, na verdade, eram enormes criaturas marinhas. Ap�s acenderem fogueiras, a �ilha� come�ava a se mover, for.�ando os marinheiros a fugirem para salvar suas vidas. No s�culo XIII, o cosm�grafo Al-Qazvini tamb�m relata a hist�ria de uma tartaruga-marinha gigantesca, confundida com uma ilha pe.los navegantes que, ao acenderem fogo, a despertavam.\rUma vers�o crist� desse mito aparece na Navega��o de S�o Brand�o, onde monges acredi.tam ter encontrado uma ilha segura para cozinhar, apenas para descobrir que estavam sobre um imenso peixe chamado Jasconye. Esses relatos, variando nas formas e contextos, mostram como o mito do Zarat� uniu diferentes tradi��es culturais, refor�ando o temor e o mist�rio das vastid�es do mar.\rO Aspidochelone, uma figura do Physiologus e dos besti�rios medievais, � uma criatura semelhante ao Zarat�, descrita ora como uma grande baleia, ora como uma vasta tartaruga marinha com espinhos nas costas. Sempre descrito como imenso, o Aspidochelone � frequen.temente confundido com uma ilha devido � sua apar�ncia, coberta de areia e vegeta��o. Ele atrai marinheiros ao fazer com que desembarquem na sua carapa�a, apenas para submergir e afog�-los.\rZarat� / Aspidochelone\rZarat� and Aspidochelone are central figures in maritime legends spanning various cultures and eras, always associated with the idea of gigantic creatures disguised as islands. These sto.ries reflect the fascination of ancient cultures with the mystery of the sea and the dangers it conceals. Both creatures share the ability to lure sailors with the harmless appearance of an island, only to reveal their true nature and bring death to those who come ashore.\rThe legend of Zarat� originates in Arab and medieval European sources. In the works of the 9th-century Muslim zoologist Al-Jahiz, sailors recount tales of �islands� that were, in fact, enor.mous sea creatures. After lighting fires, the �island� would begin to move, forcing the sailors to flee for their lives. In the 13th century, the cosmographer Al-Qazvini also tells of a gigantic sea turtle mistaken for an island by sailors who, upon lighting a fire, awakened it.\rA Christian version of this myth appears in the Voyage of Saint Brendan, where monks be.lieve they have found a safe island to cook on, only to discover they are atop an immense fish named Jasconye. These accounts, varying in form and context, show how the myth of Zarat� united different cultural traditions, reinforcing the fear and mystery of the vastness of the sea.\rThe Aspidochelone, a figure from the Physiologus and medieval bestiaries, is a creature sim.ilar to Zarat�, described either as a giant whale or a vast sea turtle with spines on its back. Always immense, the Aspidochelone is often mistaken for an island due to its appearance, covered in sand and vegetation. It lures sailors by enticing them to disembark on its shell, only to submerge and drown them.\r\r\rZaratustra\rZaratustra, tamb�m conhecido como Zoroastro, foi um profeta e fil�sofo persa, fundador do Zoroastrismo, religi�o que influenciou o Imp�rio�Aquem�nida�e possivelmente a primeira a adoptar uma perspectiva �tica e monote�sta. Nasceu na P�rsia (actual Ir�o) numa data incer.ta, entre o segundo mil�nio e o s�culo�VII�a.C. Segundo a tradi��o, desde crian�a Zaratustra demonstrou caracter�sticas m�sticas, e, ap�s anos de medita��o, relatou receber revela��es de�Ahura Mazda, o deus do Bem, ensinando uma mensagem de livre-arb�trio e o dever de es.colha entre o bem e o mal.\rO Zoroastrismo, baseado nas escrituras dos Gatas (hinos de sua autoria), define um dualismo c�smico: a eterna luta entre�Ahura Mazda e Angra Mainyu, o esp�rito do mal. A miss�o humana seria cultivar �bons pensamentos, boas palavras e boas ac��es�, visando apoiar a vit�ria final do bem. Os princ�pios�morais�inclu�am veracidade, justi�a, coopera��o e o respeito � natureza.\rO Zoroastrismo tornou-se a religi�o oficial da P�rsia at� a chegada do Isl�o, sobrevivendo posteriormente entre os�parses, uma comunidade que migrou para a �ndia, onde preservam at� hoje essa f� ancestral. A doutrina zoroastriana influenciou outras tradi��es, como o Juda�s.mo, o Cristianismo e o Islamismo, especialmente em conceitos de c�u e inferno, julgamento e livre-arb�trio.\rZarathustra\rZarathustra, also known as Zoroaster, was a Persian prophet and philosopher, founder of Zoroastrianism, a religion that influenced the Achaemenid Empire and was possibly the first to adopt an ethical and monotheistic perspective. He was born in Persia (modern-day Iran) at an uncertain date, between the second millennium and the 7th century BCE. According to tradi.tion, Zarathustra displayed mystical traits from a young age, and after years of meditation, he claimed to have received revelations from Ahura Mazda, the god of Good, teaching a message of free will and the duty to choose between good and evil.\rZoroastrianism, based on the scriptures of the Gathas (hymns authored by him), defines a cosmic dualism: the eternal struggle between Ahura Mazda and Angra Mainyu, the spirit of evil. Humanity�s mission was to cultivate �good thoughts, good words, and good deeds�, aiming to support the final victory of good. Moral principles included truthfulness, justice, cooperation, and respect for nature.\rZoroastrianism became the official religion of Persia until the arrival of Islam, later surviving among the Parsis, a community that migrated to India, where they preserve this ancient faith to this day. The Zoroastrian doctrine influenced other traditions, such as Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, particularly in concepts of heaven and hell, judgment, and free will.\r\r\rZ� do Telhado \rZ� do Telhado cujo nome verdadeiro era Jos� Teixeira da Silva (1818-1875), foi um famoso salteador do per�odo p�s-guerra civil em Portugal, reconhecido por distribuir parte dos seus roubos aos pobres, o que lhe trouxe popularidade. Nascido na aldeia do Telhado, Penafiel, de uma fam�lia humilde, aprendeu o of�cio de tratador e castrador de animais. Casou-se com a pri.ma e teve cinco filhos. Serviu como militar nos Lanceiros de Lisboa e participou na guerra civil entre l