almente, o Z� Povinho era representado de forma passiva e conformada, mas com o tempo ganhou express�o tridimensional, popularizando-se nas cer�micas das Caldas da Rai.nha. Com o famoso gesto do manguito (o �Toma!�), ele expressa revolta e insol�ncia contra as injusti�as, sendo simultaneamente retratado como paciente e submisso, mas tamb�m revolta.do e resmung�o. A figura tornou-se um s�mbolo da cr�tica social e pol�tica em Portugal, repre.sentando as contradi��es do povo portugu�s frente � corrup��o e opress�o.\rImagem inspirada num desenho de Rafael Bordalo pinheiro\rZ� Povinho\rZ� Povinho is a satirical character created by Rafael Bordalo Pinheiro in 1875, serving as a social critique and personification of the Portuguese people. He first appeared in a caricature published in the periodical A Lanterna M�gica, depicted as a resigned figure, a victim of taxes and political injustices, especially under the government of Serpa Pimentel and Fontes Pereira de Melo.\rOriginally, Z� Povinho was portrayed as passive and conformist, but over time, he gained three-dimensional representation and became popular in the ceramics of Caldas da Rainha. With his famous �manguito� gesture (the defiant �Take that!�), he expresses rebellion and in.solence against injustices, embodying both patient submission and outspoken defiance. The figure has become a symbol of social and political critique in Portugal, representing the contra.dictions of the Portuguese people in the face of corruption and oppression.\rAn image inspired by a drawing by Rafael Bordalo Pinheiro.\r\r\rZeus\rZeus, na mitologia grega, � o rei dos deuses e controlador dos c�us, rel�mpagos, e da justi�a, ocupando uma posi��o de autoridade sobre o pante�o ol�mpico. Filho do tit� Cronos e de Reia, ele � o ca�ula dos irm�os. Cronos, temendo ser deposto por um dos seus filhos, devorava-os ao nascer; por�m, Reia escondeu Zeus em Creta e deu a Cronos uma pedra no seu lugar. Quando adulto, Zeus for�ou Cronos a vomitar os seus irm�os e liderou uma rebeli�o contra os tit�s, culminando na Titanomaquia, onde os tit�s foram derrotados e aprisionados no T�rtaro.\rAp�s a vit�ria, Zeus dividiu o cosmos com seus irm�os: ficou com o c�u, enquanto Posid�o governou os mares e Hades o mundo subterr�neo. Como l�der, Zeus delegava fun��es aos deu.ses e exercia justi�a, tamb�m era padroeiro da hospitalidade, juramentos e do com�rcio. Os seus s�mbolos s�o o raio, a �guia, o touro e o carvalho. Artistas gregos o retratavam em poses majestosas, em p� com um raio ou sentado num trono.\rA mitologia tamb�m destaca os seus in�meros romances com deusas, mortais e ninfas, o que gerou v�rios descendentes divinos e her�is como Atena, Apolo, �rtemis, Dioniso, H�racles e Helena de Tr�ia. Os seus casamentos inclu�ram M�tis e, mais tarde, Hera, com quem teve Ares, Hebe e Hefesto, embora ele tamb�m seja associado a outras deusas como Leto, Dem�ter e Maia, e a mortais como S�mele e Europa. Hera, sua esposa, � conhecida pela sua inveja e constantes conflitos com as amantes e filhos de Zeus.\rZeus assumiu aspectos de um deus protector do c�u e da ordem na Gr�cia antiga, e no neoplatonismo foi associado ao Demiurgo, o criador divino. Diversos ep�tetos reflectem seus diferentes pap�is, como Zeus Ol�mpio (rei dos deuses), Zeus X�nio (protector da hospitalidade) e Zeus �rquio (guardi�o dos juramentos), reafirmando a sua abrangente autoridade sobre os deuses e os homens.\rZeus\rZeus, in Greek mythology, is the king of the gods and ruler of the skies, lightning, and jus.tice, holding a position of authority over the Olympian pantheon. Son of the Titan Cronus and Rhea, he is the youngest of his siblings. Cronus, fearing he would be overthrown by one of his children, devoured them at birth; however, Rhea hid Zeus in Crete and gave Cronus a stone in his place. Once grown, Zeus forced Cronus to regurgitate his siblings and led a rebellion against the Titans, culminating in the Titanomachy, where the Titans were defeated and imprisoned in Tartarus.\rAfter the victory, Zeus divided the cosmos with his brothers: he took the sky, while Poseidon governed the seas and Hades the underworld. As leader, Zeus delegated responsibilities to the gods and administered justice; he was also the patron of hospitality, oaths, and commerce. His symbols include the thunderbolt, the eagle, the bull, and the oak tree. Greek artists portrayed him in majestic poses, standing with a thunderbolt or seated on a throne.\rThe mythology also highlights his numerous romantic affairs with goddesses, mortals, and nymphs, which resulted in various divine and heroic offspring such as Athena, Apollo, Arte.mis, Dionysus, Heracles, and Helen of Troy. His marriages included Metis and, later, Hera, with whom he had Ares, Hebe, and Hephaestus, though he was also linked to other goddesses such as Leto, Demeter, and Maia, as well as mortals like Semele and Europa. His wife Hera was known for her jealousy and frequent conflicts with Zeus�s lovers and children.\rZeus took on the role of protector of the sky and order in ancient Greece and was associ.ated with the Demiurge, the divine creator, in Neoplatonism. His various epithets reflect his wide-ranging roles, such as Zeus Olympios (king of the gods), Zeus Xenios (protector of hospital.ity), and Zeus Horkios (guardian of oaths), reaffirming his overarching authority over gods and men alike.\r\r\rZiz\rZizʎ uma ave gigante da mitologia judaica, descrita como t�o grande que as suas asas blo.queiam a luz do sol. Ele � considerado um arqu�tipo de criaturas monstruosas e faz parte de um trio mitol�gico, junto ao�Behemoth�(uma fera terrestre) e ao Leviat� (uma criatura marinha), simbolizando a grandiosidade da cria��o divina. Embora n�o haja relatos directos na B�blia, o�Zizʎ mencionado em 2 Cr�nicas 20:16, onde � associado a um caminho pelo qual ex�rcitos inimigos se aproximaram de Jud�.\rNa tradi��o, o�Ziz�protege as criaturas a�reas, assim como o�Behemoth�protege os animais terrestres e o Leviat� cuida das criaturas marinhas. Ele � um s�mbolo de�poder�e mist�rio no fol.clore judaico, e alguns criacionistas identificaram-no como semelhante ao pterossauro�Quet.zalcoatlus, o maior animal alado da hist�ria da Terra. A refer�ncia ao�Ziz�aparece em textos antigos, mas sua presen�a � mais reconhecida como uma figura aleg�rica que representa o�po.der�divino e o equil�brio da natureza.\rZiz\rZiz is a giant bird from Jewish mythology, described as being so large that its wings block the sunlight. It is considered an archetype of monstrous creatures and is part of a mythological trio alongside Behemoth (a giant land beast) and Leviathan (a colossal sea creature), symbolizing the grandeur of divine creation. Although there are no direct accounts in the Bible, Ziz is mentioned in 2 Chronicles 20:16, where it is associated with a path by which enemy armies approached Judah.\rIn tradition, Ziz protects aerial creatures, just as Behemoth protects land animals and Le.viathan cares for sea creatures. It is a symbol of power and mystery in Jewish folklore, and some creationists have identified it as being similar to the pterosaur Quetzalcoatlus, the larg.est flying animal in Earth�s geological history. The reference to Ziz appears in ancient texts, but its presence is more recognized as an allegorical figure that represents divine power and the balance of nature.\r\r\r\r�ndice por ordem alfab�tico em portugu�s\r\r�ndice\r P�gina\r \r\r\r\r�ndice\r P�gina\r \r\r\r\rA Bao A Qu\r 10-11\r \rAbomin�vel Homem das Neves � I�ti\r 12-13\r \rAbtu e Anet\r 14\r \rAdamastor\r 15-16\r \rAd�o e Eva\r 16-17\r \rAfrodite\r 18\r \rAkhlut\r 19\r \rAladim\r 20-21\r \rAlgor�tmo\r 22\r \rAlma\r 23-24\r \rAmaterasu\r 24-25\r \rAmazonas \r 26-27\r \rAnaconda\r 28-29\r \rAnansi \r 30-31\r \rAnfisbena\r 32-33\r \rAnimais dos espelhos\r 34-35\r \rAnimais esf�ricos\r 36-37\r \rAnimais metaf�sicos\r 38-39\r \rAnimal sonhado por e S. Lewis\r 40-41\r \rAnimal sonhado por Kafka\r 42-43\r \rAnimal son